<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
So, you're saying that if my Guild takes a town and destroys the buildings in said town, the losing Guild gets paid a sum of gold equalling the cost of the lost buildings?!<P>I can deal with the concept of insurance but they should get a lesser value, perhaps half of the value of their assets.  <P>As for reason to Siege, I can think of many.<P>First and foremost of these is placement of said town.  Let&#8217;s assume for discussions sake your sworn enemies have a town in the only pass through a mountain range.  They prevent you from crossing over to do business or just adventure.  Sieging and destroying that town makes sense, especially since you should be able to plant an outpost in the very same spot, preventing them access.<P>Sieging to take away rival craftsmen makes sense as well.  Let&#8217;s say you&#8217;re town has one of the two highest ranking Smithies in the land.  It makes sense to attempt to destroy the other Smithy thus guaranteeing your town more business, more profits.  Those who are able to place and maintain the highest level craftsmen will make gold hand over fist.  They&#8217;ll also be huge targets.<P>Insurance also brings other interesting possibilities.  I think infiltration is going to be a big part of SB.  You need to know when an enemy is at his weakest.  You&#8217;re enemy is running low on resources and has to drop insurance on his property (I have absolutely no idea how insurance works so this is just speculation).  Your spies learn of this and you make your move.  Not only do you destroy their town but you prevent them from making any money via insurance.<P>Keep in mind that money might not be that easy to come by.  You have to make money to maintain your town, home and shops.  It&#8217;s very possible that gold will be in extremely short supply.  This isn&#8217;t UO after all.<P>Just some thoughts for you.   <IMG SRC="smile.gif" border="0">
</FONT>
