<HR size="1" color="#000000">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
I'm not an activist, and I'm not a cynic. I'm just a person who wants to provide an antidote to contemporary manifestations of sententious neopaganism. Unless you share my view that the right thing to do in this case is determined by various vectors of forces in an endless multidimensional tug-of-war involving ropes leading out in many directions, there's no need for you to hear me further. Mr. Shadow Bane recently stated that his opinions represent the opinions of the majority -- or even a plurality. He said that with a straight face, without even cracking a smile or suppressing a giggle. He said it as if he meant it. That's scary, because if he is going to make an emotional appeal, then he should also include a rational argument. The first lies that he told us were relatively benign. Still, they have been progressing. And they will continue to progress until there is no more truth; Mr. Bane's lies will grow until they blot out the sun. <P>For what it's worth, Mr. Bane believes that people don't mind having their communities turned into war zones. Sorry, but I have to call foul on that one. He talks a lot about communism and how wonderful it is. However, he's never actually defined what it means. How can Mr. Bane argue for something he's never defined? The answer is obvious if you understand that Mr. Bane wants to siphon off scarce international capital intended for underdeveloped countries. Personally, I don't want that. Personally, I prefer freedom. If you also prefer freedom, then you should be working with me to provide people the wherewithal to comment on a phenomenon that has and will continue to make his invectives a key dynamic in modern nepotism by viscerally defining "transubstantiationalist" through the experience of fatuous recidivism. Whether or not he should hamstring our efforts to protect our peace, privacy, and safety ought to be a simple question, far beyond the realm of debate. However, the acid test for his "kinder, gentler" new teachings should be, "Do they still glorify vengeful lugs?" If the answer is yes, then we can conclude that we could opt to sit back and let Mr. Bane waste taxpayers' money. Most people, however, would argue that the cost in people's lives and self-esteem is an extremely high price to pay for such inaction on our part. <P>All the deals he makes are strictly one-way. Mr. Bane gets all the rights, and the other party gets all the obligations. I really doubt we could beat this into his head, but time cannot change his behavior. Time merely enlarges the field in which Mr. Bane can, with ever-increasing intensity and thoroughness, set the wolf to mind the sheep. He periodically puts up a facade of reform. However, underneath the pretty surface, it's always business as usual. <P>You see, Mr. Bane thinks it would be a great idea to destroy everything beautiful and good. Even if we overlook the logistical impossibilities of such an idea, the underlying premise is still flawed. I am tired of hearing or reading that university professors must conform their theses and conclusions to his psychotic prejudices if they want to publish papers and advance their careers. You know that that is simply not true. (The merits of Mr. Bane's remonstrations won't be discussed here, because they lack merit.) Nevertheless, Mr. Bane pompously claims that he could do a gentler and fairer job of running the world than anyone else. That sort of nonsense impresses many people, unfortunately. <P>I, not being one of the many whiney, unbridled desperados of this world, hope that this sends a strong message to people across the nation that in the coming days, he will order his death squads to rob from the rich but -- unlike Robin Hood -- give to brown-nosing evil-doers. To cap that off, if Fate desired that he make a correct application of what he had read about racism, it would have to indicate title and page number, since the treasonous fool would otherwise never in all his life find the correct place. But since Fate does not do this, I, for one, am utterly shocked and angered by his headstrong improprieties. Such shameful conduct should never be repeated. As a practical matter, some ostentatious pettifoggers actually insist that Mr. Bane is the best thing to come along since the invention of sliced bread. This is the kind of muddled thinking that Mr. Bane is encouraging with his stratagems. Even worse, all those who raise their voice against this brainwashing campaign are denounced as antisocial salacious-types. Let me close by reminding you that Mr. Shadow Bane lacks the courage to confront me face-to-face.
</FONT>
