<HR size="1" color="#000000">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
<BLOCKQUOTE><font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial">quote:</font><HR> So, you're saying that if my Guild takes a town and destroys the buildings in said town, the losing Guild gets paid a sum of gold equalling the cost of the lost buildings?!  <HR></BLOCKQUOTE><P><BR>Not Equal, but a good percentage. WP is still trying to figure out the exact number. But im sure it will be 50% or more.<P> <BLOCKQUOTE><font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial">quote:</font><HR> First and foremost of these is placement of said town. Let's assume for discussions sake your sworn enemies have a town in the only pass through a mountain range. They prevent you from crossing over to do business or just adventure. Sieging and destroying that town makes sense, especially since you should be able to plant an outpost in the very same spot, preventing them access. <HR></BLOCKQUOTE><P>Yes, placement of a town could be a good reason to destroy it. I think you can take over a TOL, not sure on that one. But at best you will have to build from scratch. Soon as a major guild falls it will be EXTREMELY difficult to start another one in its place. It will be like starting a level 1 character in a zone that is for level 60's. You will be crushed quickly. That sounds like a waste of money to me. <P> <BLOCKQUOTE><font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial">quote:</font><HR> Sieging to take away rival craftsmen makes sense as well. Let's say you're town has one of the two highest ranking Smithies in the land. It makes sense to attempt to destroy the other Smithy thus guaranteeing your town more business, more profits. Those who are able to place and maintain the highest level craftsmen will make gold hand over fist. They'll also be huge targets.  <HR></BLOCKQUOTE><P>Yes, Sieging for destruction. This is always possible. But you will lose many only to weaken the strength of another guild, with that weakening yourself and opening yourself up to a counter attack by the same guild in a different location or a guild who has sworn allegiance.. If you don't wish to occupy the territory, that will work.<P><BR> <BLOCKQUOTE><font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial">quote:</font><HR> Insurance also brings other interesting possibilities. I think infiltration is going to be a big part of SB. You need to know when an enemy is at his weakest. You're enemy is running low on resources and has to drop insurance on his property (I have absolutely no idea how insurance works so this is just speculation). Your spies learn of this and you make your move. Not only do you destroy their town but you prevent them from making any money via insurance.  <HR></BLOCKQUOTE><P>That would take some pretty good eavesdropping. You would need to know what the guild leader knows, or his officers. You would need someone on the inside selling secrets. Im not sure if insurance can be lost, or taken away. <P>I wonder if your building decays, do you still get insurance? Or is it only if its destroyed?<P> <BLOCKQUOTE><font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial">quote:</font><HR> Keep in mind that money might not be that easy to come by. You have to make money to maintain your town, home and shops. It's very possible that gold will be in extremely short supply. This isn't UO after all.  <HR></BLOCKQUOTE><P>All the more reason not to take any chances. When you go to conquer another guild you will be expending great resources, But when the war is over you will have nothing to show for it. Then if you wanted to start another guild in your enemies place, that's even more resources needed. So all in all, when trying to take over another guild you better be EXTREMELY wealthy or you could lose your whole empire.<P><BR>My feeling is that "Uber" guilds will run the world eventually. They will be the only ones able to spend that kinda of coin on a war, and have enough man power to keep a new town alive while it is being reconstructed, while still providing equal protection to their main guild.
</FONT>
