</FONT>
<HR size="1" color="#000000">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
Now for my response.  This game has changed over the last year.  Perhaps the game has been adjusted to appeal to more players. I can't help but wonder if the demise of UO2 had anything to do with it.  Perhaps reality just hit with all the info that has been coming out the last 3 or so months.  I'm not sure, but I don't think the end result is what many pictured it as being a year ago.  <P>I generally try to stay positive and defend my game of choice, which it still is.  I am an admin for a fansite I kind of feel obligated.  But in all honesty I don't agree with some of the changes, or the knowledge of reality (yeah this is just being politically correct), that have come to pass.<P>Pro Everquest has hit the nail on the head of one of these changes I don't look forward to: Insurance and building ownership.  This argument already took place on the official boards.  Now while it is very hard to get your opinion in there and have it count it is also a good place to read most, if not all, the takes on something.  At least when the topic is hot, as insurance was when it was first released.  Some of the following points may be influenced by those discussions.<P>A building that degrades will not receive insurance (Ashen or Warden said so).  So if you wipe out a town and they won't sell you the buildings, put walls up around them and guards.  Eventually, they will sell or lose their money.  Of course this could take weeks at higher ranks.<P>Money will be hard to come by.  You will have to upkeep equipment.  Buy some new equipment when you are killed and looted.  Pay for your npcs in your shops, pay for your shops to be upgraded to a higher rank, pay for your npcs to be upgraded to higher ranks.  Pay rent on the shop, pay your npcs for working.  Pay for insurance.  Money sink anyone?  More like a money black hole.  Is this a bad thing?  No.  Of course there will be money incoming as well.  Taxes on sales, profit from shops, etc.    <P>I've gotten the impression that a nice city with some rank 7 buildings is going to take around a month to make.  I don't think insurance will cover the time, possibly not the upgrades.  You can't replace your npcs easily, especially rare ones.  So destroying a city or even taking ownership of it is in essence destroying someone's time.  Even taking their insurance and starting over won't quiet make up for their rank 7 smithy with 3 dwarven forgemasters.<BR>  <BR>The big point Warden was trying to make was that you have just humiliated your enemy, you own their tree of life and you want to take everything they have away from them?  Isn't the humiliation alone enough, let alone the fact that they have lost possibly months of hard work and time?  They are already down, don't kick them.  <P>Yet in their backstory there is a tale of barbarians raiding the southern lands.  How is that even possible anymore?  You don't get anything a barbarian would even want from raiding a land.  You can't just run in and steal loot and leave as far as I can tell.  An invasion has to be permanent or it's pointless.  <P>Basically it comes down to the fact that Wolfpack has decided they don't want the player really to ever lose anything completely that they have spent time to earn.  This is obviously a business decision and probably a wise one, but is it best for the game?  I don't know.  <P>I can say one thing, I was far more eager about invading a town before I knew about all this than I was before.  I didn't want to wipe out anyone's home.  I wasn't planning on raiding their banks.  I wanted to take over.  Not just a part, but the entire town (which as Algernon pointed out was the impression we were given earlier).  I don't even care if they have conquerers insurance and they get payed because I took their building by force.  They can have their money.  Why should I be the one that has to pay for it though? <BR>  <BR>Is the risk worth the reward anymore?  I'm not sure it ever really was.  Sieges will be a big event, not something that happens very often.  I'm sure if there is a siege on your world you will hear about it.  It is going to take a ton of money, you will have to plan for it in advance and prepare for it.  I think it was Dreadflame or Chewie at E3 that said he didn't expect a guild to go siege another guild's town.  Rather he expected a nation to obliterate the the other guild's town, not even giving them a fighting chance the numbers would be so against their favor.<P>Which brings me to the next point.  I don't know how long guilds will be able to operate single handedly.  Nations will form and as they do how long will your guild feel safe?  Even if you have 60 people, that nation of 4 guilds with 30 people each has to look threatening.  You'll probably want to join one yourself.  I'm not sure I'm worried about the uber guilds, I think they will fight amongst themselves.  How about the nation of uber guilds though?<P>Anyway the path of least resistance is still the same as it always was.  Take a few days off work come release, hope the beta enables them to trully have a good opening day without complications, and start earning money.  Get your guild running, buy your tree, plant it, and start building your town.<P>The game was never going to be perfect, I never planned on liking every aspect of it.  There are far too many people different than I that are also looking forward to it to hope for such a utopia.  The changes of the recent months have just made this truth more obvious.  Will the game still roxor though?  You bet it will.<P>--------------------<P>Don't blaim the programmers, it's the publisher's fault.
</FONT>
